{
  "texts": [
    "It can be seen from Figure 7 that the data points are mainly distributed in the area between the lines of R EXT Hα = 0.35 × R median Hα and R EXT Hα = 0.05 × R median Hα (indicated by a solid line and a dashed line in Figure 7, respectively).",
    "There is a positive correlation trend between log R EXT Hα and log R median Hα as exhibited by the data points in between the two lines, which is consistent with the results obtained by Lockwood et al (2007) and Hall et al (2009) through the Ca II H and K lines (see introduction in Section 1).",
    "The number density information in Figure 7 shows that most of the data points are located in the lower left region of the diagram, indicating that most stellar sources in our sample have low activity intensity and small Hα variability.",
    "However, some stellar sources with lower activity intensity (in the left part of the diagram) do exhibit large Hα variability (as large as reaching to the R EXT Hα = 0.35 × R median Hα line); while for the stellar sources with higher activity intensity (in the right part of the diagram), the data points are mainly distributed in the middle of the area enclosed by the R EXT Hα = 0.35 × R median Hα and R EXT Hα = 0.05 × R median Hα lines.",
    "The result that solar-like stars with low activity intensity do not necessarily have small variability is also found by Gomes da Silva et al (2021) using the Ca II H and K lines, which is consistent with our result obtained from the Hα line."
  ]
}